, United Kingdom","Sutherland, Scotland":"Sutherland, Scotland","Golspie, Sutherland, Scotland":"Golspie, Sutherland, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Sutherland","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish (Caithness): habitational name from the Scottish county of Sutherland, named with Old Norse <i>súthr</i> ‘south, southern’ + <i>land</i> ‘land’ because the territory lay south of Scandinavia and the Norse colonies in the Orkney and Shetland Islands.","History: This is the name of a Highland Scottish clan associated with the county of Sutherland."],"variants":[{"name":"Southerland","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Sutherland  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William Sutherland 2nd Earl of Sutherland was born about 1240, in Sutherland, Scotland, his father, William de Moravia 1st Earl of Sutherland, was 52 and his mother, Mrs. William de Moravia, was 52. He had at least 2 sons. He died on 7 July 1307, in Golspie, Sutherland, Scotland, at the age of 68."},"et":{"about 1240–7 July 1307":"umbes 1240–7. juuli 1307","1240–1307":"1240–1307","1274–1327":"1274–1327","1285–1333":"1285–1333","1190–1248":"1190–1248","1190–Female":"1190–Surnud","1190